{{Unreferenced stub|auto=yes|date=December 2009}}
'''Schallanalyse''' (pronounced {{IPA-de|ˈʃal anaˈlyzə|}}), "sound analysis,") was a method of [[poetic]] analysis developed by the renowned [[philologist]] [[Eduard Sievers]], and described in detail in his book ''Ziele und Wege der Schallanalyse'' (1924). Sievers had previously developed a system of [[Sievers' Theory of Anglo-Saxon Meter|"five types"]] to describe the rhythmic patterns found in [[Old English language|Old English]] and [[Old Saxon language|Old Saxon]] poetry, which had met with widespread acceptance. He then abandoned the five types in favor of his new model. ''Schallanalyse'', however, proved difficult to understand for even the most intelligent people in his field and had very few adherents, usually people who worked with Sievers personally.

