{{Infobox University |name = W.A. Franke College of Forestry & Conservation |image_name = University of Montana Forestry.jpg |image_size = 155px |established = 1913 |type = [[public university|Public]] |dean = Irma S. Russell |city = [[Missoula]] |state = [[Montana]] |country = USA |students = |undergrad = |postgrad = |faculty = |staff = |campus = [[University of Montana]] |website = http://www.cfc.umt.edu/ |logo = |footnotes = |coor = {{Coord|46.85808|-113.98416|format=dms|display=inline,title|type:edu_region:US-MT}} }} The '''W.A. Franke College of Forestry & Conservation''', formerly the '''University of Montana College of Forestry and Conservation''', is college within the [[University of Montana]]. It was created by an act of the Thirteenth Montanan Legislative Assembly in 1913 to meet the great and growing demand on the part of lumber companies, large timber holding corporations, and the national and state governments.<ref>Twentieth Register of the University of Montana 1914-1915. p.193</ref>
==Laboratories and Stations== The College of Forestry and Conservation has access to well-equipped laboratories, extensive computer technology, and four field stations -- # the {{convert|28000|acre|km2|adj=on}} Lubrecht Experimental Forest # the [[Flathead Lake]] Biological Station on the shores of {{convert|184|sqmi|km2|adj=on}} Flathead Lake # the {{convert|3500|acre|km2|adj=on}} Bandy Ranch # the [[Boone and Crockett Club]]'s [[Theodore Roosevelt]] Memorial Ranch of {{convert|6000|acre|km2}} along the east face of the [[Rocky Mountains|Rockies]].
==Program== The College of Forestry and Conservation is currently ranked number one in the country.
==Building== The [[Buildings at the University of Montana#Forestry Building|Forestry Building]] is one of the oldest buildings on campus. It was built in the Renaissance Revival style specified by Carsley-Gilbert’s master plan in 1922.
